BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Writing After Dartmouth: Panel Discussion
DTSTART;TZID=America/New_York:20260724T123000
DTEND;TZID=America/New_York:20260724T133000
DTSTAMP:20260720T121142Z
UID:dartmouth-82098@free-food-dartmouth
DESCRIPTION:Original event page(s):\nhttps://home.dartmouth.edu/events/eve
 nt?event=82098\n\nDescription:\nAsk a stellar panel of recent Dartmouth al
 umnae about grad school\, writing\, publishing\, and navigating the years 
 after college. This panel discussion will be moderated by Professor Alexan
 der Chee.\nA light lunch will be provided. Registration encouraged. Please
  email\nlaura.jean.gilloux@dartmouth.edu.\nAbout the Panelists\nCarolyn Si
 lverstein ’21\nearned her MFA in Creative Writing from Colorado State Un
 iversity and her BA in English Literature and Creative Writing from Dartmo
 uth College. Her writing has appeared in\nArchipelago\, Vol. III\, Stonefe
 nce Review\, the Write Launch\n\, and\nMcNeese Review\n. Her work has been
  shortlisted for the Virginia Woolf Award in Short Fiction. A native New Y
 orker\, Carolyn is a certified ski instructor and enjoys spending time wit
 h her dog\, Gatsby\, when she’s not writing.\nAllison Hufford\n’21\nis
  a graduate of Dartmouth College\, where she majored in English literature
  and minored in environmental studies.  As JRA’s Subsidiary Rights Mana
 ger\, she oversees the licensing of translation\, audio\, electronic\, boo
 k club\, and large print rights throughout the world in over fifty languag
 es. She and her team work tirelessly in collaboration with a highly skill
 ed network of foreign agents and scouts to market JRA authors and their wo
 rk internationally\, including in person at the London and Frankfurt book 
 fairs. She is an avid reader with a particular love for character-driven n
 arratives\, lyrical writing styles\, and anything with a speculative twist
 .\nElizabeth Janowski ’21\n(she/her) graduated from Dartmouth with a dou
 ble major in history and film and media studies and served as executive ed
 itor of\nThe Dartmouth\n. She received an M.S. in journalism from Columbia
  University in 2022. Elizabeth is an assistant editor at Viking Penguin\, 
 where she has worked with authors including Amor Towles\, Tana French\, Al
 ejandro Varela\, Ruth Ozeki\, Nathaniel Philbrick\, and Maggie Stiefvater.
  Originally from Milwaukee\, Elizabeth lives in New York City.\nAbout the 
 Moderator\nAlexander Chee\nis the best-selling author of the novels\nThe Q
 ueen of the Night\nand\nEdinburgh\n\, and the essay collection\nHow to Wri
 te an Autobiographical Novel\n. He is a contributing editor at\nThe New Re
 public\n\, and an editor at large at\nThe Virginia Quarterly Review\n. He 
 is the recipient of a 2021 Guggenheim Fellowship and a 2021 United States 
 Artists Fellowship\, and awards and fellowships from the Whiting Foundatio
 n and the NEA\, and residency fellowships from the MacDowell Colony\, the 
 VCCA\, Civitella Ranieri and Amtrak. He is a professor of English and Crea
 tive Writing at Dartmouth College and the chair of the Dartmouth Literary 
 Arts Bridge.\n\nSponsor / organizer: Literary Arts Bridge\n\nAudience: Pub
 lic\n\nSource: Dartmouth\n\nWhy this was included: explicit food-service w
 ording\; food keyword near service context\n\nFood availability is inferre
 d from the source listing\; verify details before attending.
LOCATION:Literary Arts Bridge (7 Lebanon St. Suite 105)
STATUS:CONFIRMED
URL:https://home.dartmouth.edu/events/event?event=82098
END:VEVENT
